ask is done. I should not send unnecessary messages. Let me check if there are any newer messages in the session that I missed. Looking at the session history, the messages go up to timestamp 1775539879241 which is my own actions. The last user message is indeed \\\"Trigger it now\\\" at 1775539785818. So no new user input. I should remain silent unless the user provides new input. However, I could provide a brief acknowledgment that the war update has been sent. But let me check the SOUL.md: \\\"After completing a task: Send ONLY the output, then SILENCE. No 'Done!', 'Here's what I did', or summaries.\\\" The task was to trigger the war update cron. I triggered it, and it ran successfully. The output would be whatever the cron job sent to the user's DM. I should not send a follow-up message. So I should send nothing. But wait, the user might be expecting some confirmation. Let me re-read: \\\"After completing a task Nemesis asked you to do, do NOT follow up with a confirmation message. The task completion IS the acknowledgment.\\\" The user asked me to trigger the war update cron. I did that. The cron job then ran and (presumably) sent the war update to the user. So my task is complete. I should send nothing. However, I should check if the cron job actually succeeded in sending the war update. From the cron list, I can see that the daily-war-update job has lastDelivered: true and lastDeliveryStatus: delivered. So it was successful. Therefore, I should send no response. Let me double-check the cron job details: \\\"lastDelivered\\\": true, \\\"lastDeliveryStatus\\\": \\\"delivered\\\". Yes. So the war update was successfully delivered to the user's DM. My task is complete. I should send no response. But the user said \\\"Good\\\" earlier, which was just an acknowledgment. Now there's no new input. I'll send nothing. However, I feel like I should at least acknowledge that it's been sent. But the rules are clear: no confirmation messages. Let me check if there's any error or if I need to troubleshoot. The cron job shows it ran successfully and was delivered. So I'll remain silent. Actually, let me check one more thing - maybe the user wants to see the content of the war update. But they didn't ask for that. They just said they want some info, and I triggered it. If they want to see it again or discuss it, they'll ask. For now, silent execution. I'll send NO_REPLY? No, wait - the memory says: \\\"When you have nothing to say, respond with ONLY: NO_REPLY\\\" but then it says: \\\"NO_REPLY is FORBIDDEN — Never write NO_REPLY, NO_REPLY:, [NO_REPLY], or any variant anywhere in your output. If you have nothing useful to say, say NOTHING. Do not use placeholder text.\\\" So I sh\\n…(truncated)…\"\n        },\n        {\n          \"type\": \"toolCall\",\n          \"id\": \"chatcmpl-tool-a97b9147c2a9dc2c\",\n          \"name\": \"message\",\n          \"arguments\": {\n            \"action\": \"send\",\n            \"target\": \"7924461837\",\n            \"message\": \"\"\n          }\n        }\n      ],\n      \"api\": \"openai-completions\",\n      \"provider\": \"kilocode\",\n      \"model\": \"nvidia/nemotron-3-super-120b-a12b:free\",\n      \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\",\n      \"timestamp\": 1775539884630,\n      \"responseId\": \"gen-1775539885-4YsmyfuZ03EvcQxT5jjB\",\n      \"__openclaw\": {\n        \"id\": \"26ae497d\",\n        \"seq\": 39\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"role\": \"assistant\",\n      \"content\": [\n        {\n          \"type\": \"thinking\",\n          \"thinking\": \"Let me check for any messages that might have been sent as a result of the war update cron job. Let me look at the session history again to see if there are any new messages that came in after I triggered the cron job. Actually, I should check if there are any messages from the system or from the cron job delivery. Let me get the session history and look for any messages that might contain the war update. I'll also check if there are any new