ge. So I should send nothing. But wait, the user might be expecting some confirmation. Let me re-read: \\\"After completing a task Nemesis asked you to do, do NOT follow up with a confirmation message. The task completion IS the acknowledgment.\\\" The user asked me to trigger the war update cron. I did that. The cron job then ran and (presumably) sent the war update to the user. So my task is complete. I should send nothing. However, I should check if the cron job actually succeeded in sending the war update. From the cron list, I can see that the daily-war-update job has lastDelivered: true and lastDeliveryStatus: delivered. So it was successful. Therefore, I should send no response. Let me double-check the cron job details: \\\"lastDelivered\\\": true, \\\"lastDeliveryStatus\\\": \\\"delivered\\\". Yes. So the war update was successfully delivered to the user's DM. My task is complete. I should send no response. But the user said \\\"Good\\\" earlier, which was just an acknowledgment. Now there's no new input. I'll send nothing. However, I feel like I should at least acknowledge that it's been sent. But the rules are clear: no confirmation messages. Let me check if there's any error or if I need to troubleshoot. The cron job shows it ran successfully and was delivered. So I'll remain silent. Actually, let me check one more thing - maybe the user wants to see the content of the war update. But they didn't ask for that. They just said they want some info, and I triggered it. If they want to see it again or discuss it, they'll ask. For now, silent execution. I'll send NO_REPLY? No, wait - the memory says: \\\"When you have nothing to say, respond with ONLY: NO_REPLY\\\" but then it says: \\\"NO_REPLY is FORBIDDEN — Never write NO_REPLY, NO_REPLY:, [NO_REPLY], or any variant anywhere in your output. If you have nothing useful to say, say NOTHING. Do not use placeholder text.\\\" So I sh... (truncated)\\n\"\n        },\n        {\n          \"type\": \"toolCall\",\n  