y with a timestamp after when it started running.\n\nLet me get the session history and look for messages with timestamps after 1775540345732.\n\nI'll get the session history and then look at the timestamps of the messages.\n\nActually, let me just look at the session history I already have and see if I can find any messages with timestamps after that value.\n\nFrom the session history I've seen, the timestamps go up to around 1775540377092 (from the last sessions_history call), which is about 31 seconds after the job started running (1775540377092 - 1775540345732 = 31360 ms = 31.36 seconds).\n\nSo there should be plenty of time for the job to have completed and sent a message.\n\nLet me look through the session history for any assistant messages that have timestamps after 1775540345732 and contain substantive content.\n\nActually, let me check if there are any messages at all that I haven't seen yet. Let me get the session history and look at all the messages, focusing on those with timestamps after the job start time.\n\nI'll get the session history and then inspect it.\n\nBut before that, let me think: maybe the job encountered an error and didn't send a message. Or maybe it's still running.\n\nLet me check the runs for the job again to see if it has completed. I'll get the runs and see if there are any entries.\n\nActually, let me check if there's a way to see the output of the job directly. Since it's an agentTurn, maybe I can check if there are any logs or if I can see what it produced.\n\nAlternatively, let me just run the war update script manually in a way that I can see the output. Let me execute the python script directly and see what it does - but that would just create another cron job.\n\nActually, let me check if there are any recent errors in the cron jobs or if I can see any output from the job execution.\n\nLet me look at the session history for any error messages or output from the cron job.\n\nActually, let me try a different approach. Let me check if the user has received any new messages by seeing if there are any user messages in the session history that I missed? No, that wouldn't make sense.\n\nLet me look for any system messages or messages from the cron job delivery.\n\nActually, let me just assume that the job has completed and sent the message, and that I need to look for it in the session history. Let me examine the session history more carefully for any message that looks like a war update.\n\nI'll get the session history and then look for any assistant message that contains the kind of content that would be in a war update.\n\nLet me do that now.\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"chatcmpl-tool-b14119d2b773f13a","name":"sessions_history","arguments":{"sessionKey":"agent:main:telegram:direct:7924461837","limit":500}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"kilocode","model":"nvidia/nemotron-3-super-120b-a12b:free","usage":{"input":94251,"output":4309,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":98560,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775540427390,"responseId":"gen-1775540428-N4WcrpxbGKUYNwjbDBHY"}}
